description: Henry Fillmore ranks in the top five of American march composers, and his "Circus Bee" is a great example of his mastery! A favorite of circus bandleader Merle Evans, this march will thrill your audience!
This great circus “screamer” has been a favorite of bands worldwide for over a century, and it will thrill your audience from downbeat to stinger!
"Waterville Military Band"
from "Prince Ananias"
This bright 6/8 march evokes a sense of patriotism, and will have toes tapping all throughout the audience.
This great circus “screamer” has been a favorite of bands worldwide for over a century, and it will thrill your audience from downbeat to stinger!
The saxophone parts may be played as a quartet
Contains a saxophone quartette that can be used as a stand-alone quartette or with band accompaniment
*NOTE: Do not make any pauses for dancing
S. E. Morse is known only for this vibrant and stirring parade march, appropriately titled "Up The Street." Solid and stirring!
"The Kilties" is a jaunty 6/8 march featuring quotations from well-known Scottish tunes. One of the truly great "old-line" marches from the classic concert band era.

titre: Pack Up Your Troubles In Your Old Kit-Bag

description: Written for his band's frequent performances at the popular New Jersey summer resort area of Asbury Park, New Jersey, this rock-solid Arthur Pryor march is tops!
"Founded on the Chord of the seventh"
Commissioned by the Sousa Band Fraternal Society on the centennial of Sousa’s birth, this is perhaps Leonard’s finest march. Brilliant!

This excellent march was written during Leonard Smith's tenure in the Phildalephia Navy Yard Band during WWII, and was dedicated to Admiral Milo Draemel. It features a virtuoso euphonium obbligato in the trio. Top-notch!
From the Comic Opera "The American Maid"
One of Sousa’s most melodic and tuneful marches! Composed 1908.
Written in 1915 to honor the Panama Canal, this excellent Sousa march was premiered at the Panama-Pacific Exposition in San Francisco. Brilliant variation technique in the trio!
One of Sousa’s brilliant WWI patriotic marches. Dignified and rousing!
This 1893 Sousa gem was named for the popular New York summer resort area, frequently visited by the Sousa Band.

At the end of WW I Sousa seized on a happy moment of victory to compose a joyous song of celebration welcoming home the returning troops. His stirring “march song” is now available in a new edition for concert band.
titre: When The Boys Come Sailing Home

description: Sousa’s most famous two-step march, which created a musical craze when first introduced!
An early Sousa classic (1889). Features trumpets and drums in "reginemtal" style.
The most famous march ever composed, and the official march of the United States of America. Reprinted from the original 1897 edition.
This classic “old line” march features the cornets and drums a la “regimental” style. Familiar patriotic tunes shine in this Americana treasure!
CLEVER! Andy Clark has arranged the classic “Jingle Bells’’ in three popular styles that your audience will love. Medium Easy.
Written in 1915 to honor the Panama Canal, this excellent Sousa march was premiered at the Panama-Pacific Exposition in San Francisco. Brilliant variation technique in the trio!

There are composers about whom nothing or only little is known, who are only known through their works or even through one work only. Luigi Carvelli is one of them: He lived in the second half of the 19th century and died afterthe turn of the century. Carvelli is supposed to have been a hornist in the area of Torino/Milan and played at the world premiere of Verdi's 'Falstaff'. The only extant work is his 'Serenata
Outstanding traditional 6/8 March for young bands. (Incl. 4 scores)
You won’t go wrong with this impressive concert march for young bands. (incl. 4 scores)
Excellent concert march with a slightly “Scottish’’ flavor. Check out this one! (incl. 4 scores)
Bold dynamic overture for medium level bands. (incl. 4 scores)
A truly strong traditional March at the medium difficult grade leve. A wonderful sounding march that is not only fun and easy to play, but will also save you valuable rehearsal time!
Comes complete with two-part vocal score. Perfect for combining Band and Chorus.
This classic “old line” march features the cornets and drums a la “regimental” style. Familiar patriotic tunes shine in this Americana treasure!

The sparkling opening of this dramatic overture along with triumphant brass sounds set the stage for an engaging musical journey. Beautiful melodic moments and rhythmic interest will keep musicians and audience engaged from beginning to end. Wonderful!

A dramatic and beautiful treatment of this well-known hymn. The ingenious use of the first interval from the chorale sets the stage for more creativity to come. A brief clarinet solo begins the development. The piece evolves throughout to a powerful finale. Stunning!
titre: Chorale Prelude: Rejoice Ye Pure In Heart

description: Magnificent and full of musical variety, this outstanding work will set your band apart. Solidly scored to sound full and well-balanced. Effective for both sacred and secular performances.
titre: Chorale Prelude On A German Hymn Tune

description: This overture is perfect for exposing less experienced players to mixed meter. Creatively scored, with thoughtful development, this piece can work well with small bands. An excellent teaching tool.

Following a bold beginning, this piece comes alive utilizing a spirited circle dance as the main programmatic material. This captivating work has become a favorite. Excellent for festivals or to liven up any performance.

Dance-like in nature, this setting of the Brazilian folk song "Tutu Maramba” explores a variety of musical textures. A wonderful opportunity for the percussion section to create an authentic Latin percussion feel.
titre: Beguine On A Brazilian Folk Song

description: A stirring masterpiece which begins with an imaginative introduction using fragments of the theme. As the work develops, the tonality also changes between major and minor keys evolving into the next section, using the familiar Civil War melody "When Johnny Comes Marching Home." An off-stage cadenza follows with muffled drums and muted trumpets. The triumphant finale is sparked by a modulation accompanied by a
Written in the great European march style, this wonderful piece has great musical appeal without overly technical demands.

A concert work perfect for young bands. The opening section, labeled andante and maestoso, features two distinct themes. The second theme is used again in the B section at a brighter tempo with an accented style. Varying key changes, tempo changes and one 7/8 measure, will make this appealing and interesting to young concert bands.
This concert medley is based on some of America's favorite folk songs: "When Johnny Comes Marching Home," "Aura Lee" and "Bound for the Promised Land." A trumpet solo is featured in "Aura Lee"

A magnificent arrangement. Beautifully harmonized from the opening flute solo through the development of the theme and building to a triumphant end. This piece works well with bands of all ages and is a moving and effective finale. An excellent choice for massed bands.

This concert piece displays lyrical themes and challenging rhythmic motives including a 7/8 measure which has become a trademark of Claude’s writing. A perfect choice for an advanced middle school or less experienced high school group. A contest favorite!

This overture features a clarinet solo in the opening section whose theme is echoed throughout. A strong selection with reasonable technical demands, this piece is perfect for contest and festival use.
Opening with a bold and powerful statement, this piece introduces repetitive rhythmic and thematic fragments, slowly at first, and building to an energetic and dramatic finish.

This spirited overture begins with a trumpet solo with additional solo opportunities for flute, trombone, clarinet and horn. The saxophone, flute/oboe and percussion sections are also featured. The challenges in this piece, which will justify the "5" rating, are: fourteen meter changes; eight tempo changes; and a journey through four concert keys. A perfect showcase for accomplished high school and college ensembles.
Contrasting tempos and timbres propel the excitement in this contrasting and rhythmic work. Particularly demanding for percussionists. Well-suited for contest and festival performances.
Feelings of a South American festival come to life through fiery brass and percussion writing and a hint of Latin jazz. Sure to be a favorite of performers and audiences. Chido!

This concert march contains tutti passages perfect for focusing on balance within the ensemble. The overall effectiveness of this rhythmic, choral march is enhanced by a slightly slower tempo. A great teaching composition.

One of the most well-designed melodic works of Claude T. Smith. This piece is skillfully written with careful selection of range, keys, articulations and patterns, making it sound much more difficult than it really is. Spectacular!

This is one of Claude's most difficult later works. An excellent choice for outstanding high school, university and professional bands looking for a challenge. Great writing throughout; featuring a bass clarinet cadenza and solos for the alto saxophone and flute. Worth the effort!

Subtitled, "A Festival Fanfare Selection," this work is at times dramatic and graceful. Featuring 7/8 bars, quarter-note triplets, accents off the beat and driving eighth notes which drive and add power. Scored with cross-cueing. Always a favorite of middle level bands!

Full, resonant scoring, moderate ranges and interesting rhythmic themes are the hallmark of this captivating overture. Exceptional teaching choice for advanced middle school and high school bands and an effective way to showcase your group for concerts or festivals.

This work is a skillful blend of both the medieval Spanish dance form and contemporary ballet. Through a set of dance variations which contrast in mood and meter, the work unfolds through challenging rhythmic patterns and interwoven individual parts for each section, especially the percussionists. Creative, educational and engaging.
Written by French composer, Gustave Louis Ganne and skillfully transcribed by Claude T. Smith. Classic yet contemporary.

Based on the well-known Irish air, "Minstrel Boy," and harmonized in a traditional manner but with the special flair and treatment of Claude T. Smith. A delightful and alluring addition to any band library.

This overture lends itself to the accomplished high school band and offers solo opportunities to the flute, trumpet, tuba, oboe, and bassoon. Using contrasting tempo and meter changes, this work will be an ensemble favorite and audience pleaser.
Feature the percussion section with this melodic beguine. Syncopated rhythms will challenge and drive each section throughout making this a wonderful change of pace at your next performance.

Through the use of a main theme and extensive fugal development, this piece has a distinct musical character. An intricate and intense work for advanced middle school and high school bands. Intriguing!
CLEVER! Andy Clark has arranged the classic “Jingle Bells’’ in three popular styles that your audience will love. Medium Easy.

This poignant work will provide your band the opportunity to feature expressive ensemble playing with masterful orchestration for interwoven woodwind and brass lines. This newly revised version features an expanded percussion section that tastefully supports the engaging melodies by the woodwinds and brass. A beautifully lyric selection to complement your programs.
titre: Leaves That Descend To No Drum

description: A wonderfully spirited march, Bound Away pays homage to the state of Missouri, and its namesake river, by using the melody of Shenandoah (also known as Across the Wide Missouri) as material throughout the march. An excellent addition to a festival program or concert.
sous_titre: Concert March featuring Across the Wide Missouri

description: The powerful opening of Table Rock Festival leads to bright flute solo. Composed in a traditional ABA’ overture form, the serene middle section is surrounded by lively 6/8 sections with a jaunty melody that sticks with the listener. This will complement any concert or festival program.

What kind of music would Mozart write if he were alive today and had been exposed to jazz, rock 'n' roll, and polytonality? This piece supposes that he would start with what he knew and then figure it out on the fly! Mozart's Sandbox is a piece rich with depth and humor, but thoughtfully scored for young bands.

“God of Our Fathers” is based on the hymn with the same name and is one of the most iconic American Christian hymns dating back to the 19th-century. Claude T. Smith’s concert band arrangement of this hymn has become a staple of band literature. This flexible arrangement allows ensembles to perform the work with as few as fourteen musicians providing accessibility and flexibility for numerous instrumentation needs,

Concert Variations” was written for the Lambda Chapter of Phi Beta Mu and originally premiered at the Missouri Music Educators Convention in 1975. This flexible arrangement allows ensembles to perform the work with as few as thirteen musicians providing accessibility and flexibility for numerous instrumentation needs, while still allowing a full ensemble sound. *The posted recording is based on the full band scoring

Translated as “Sound of The Winds”, “Sonus Ventorum” begins with a dramatic opening for full band segueing into an energetic allegro section. This flexible arrangement allows ensembles to perform the work with as few as fourteen musicians providing accessibility and flexibility for numerous instrumentation needs, while still allowing a full ensemble sound. The posted recording is based on the full band scoring but

“Dramatic Prelude” begins with a “dramatic” fanfare, which is followed by an easily accessible melody; a del segno takes you back to the “dramatic” fanfare and an ending as exciting as the beginning. This flexible arrangement allows ensembles to perform the work with as few as twelve musicians providing accessibility and flexibility for numerous instrumentation needs, while still allowing a full ensemble sound.

A bold opening starts this previously unpublished march. Written in the style of a classic circus march, this piece has something in it for everyone. The tasteful use of contemporary harmonies at key points add a fresh sound to the march genre. Plenty of opportunities for great music in this new work that has been carefully edited for the modern concert band. It is certain to be a favorite with students and

collection: Concert Band edition
description: Milestones is a celebratory concert fanfare that encapsulates the excitement of a major accomplishment or event. In true fanfare style, the piece showcases the brass with brilliant rhythmic motifs and driving woodwind and percussion parts. With its high driving energy, this piece is a perfect concert opener!
Bring a touch of history into your next performance. This epic musical tribute includes narration and SATB choir. Powerful!
titre: Harry S Truman - A Musical Tribute

description: One of Claude T. Smith's last completed works, "Raise Your Voice in Song" was commissioned by the Nebraska Music Educators Association for the 50th Anniversary on NMEA! It was written for the 1986 All-State Band, Choir and Orchestra for their combined performance on November 22, 1986 in Hastings, NE. This majestic work lends itself as a finale, for band alone, or a combined performance with string orchestra and/or

Previously unpublished, "Honor Guard March" was composed by Claude T. Smith in 1959 while he was teaching in Cozad, NE. Premiered in 1961, this march has remained unknown until now! Written in traditional form, this march contains a contemporary flair and sound that is unique to this composer's distinctive style. Featuring an unusual meter shift (from 6/8 to alla breve at the trio) this march is an excellent choice
The three sections of this masterwork (I. Intrada, II. Serenade, and III. Scherzo) challenge and excite while traveling through a variety of meter changes. Impressive!
titre: Three Contrasts For Solo Horn and Wind Ensemble

description: A marvelous piece written to commemorate a community and it’s musicians. Lushly scored to bring forth vivid imagery, this programmatic work is one that your musicians will enjoy performing. Simply stunning.

'Staunton Road March' is a delightful march written in the style of the classic circus marches. The brilliant obligato at the end showcases the talents of your upper woodwinds. An excellent addition to any concert program.

Cast as a pseudo-Chaconne, this set of variations on the popular tune “Amazing Grace” offers something new for your band. This new work features a prominent piano solo and accessible parts for each instrument. Also available for orchestra.

Styled in the popular vein of Mannheim Steamroller, Overture to Joy will give any band concert an energetic boost! Scored mostly in 7/8 time, this hard-driving version of Beethoven's infamous "Ode to Joy" along with other well-known songs is a joyful addition to any holiday program! Also available for orchestra.
This arrangement of the traditional English carol is a perfect addition to a holiday concert for younger and mature bands. Delightful and elegant.

Bring the exciting “twang” of the Ozark region’s most famous songs to your performance hall with this exhilarating setting of the popular fiddle tune, Arkansas Traveler. Your band will love playing the zany variations of a simple tune most of them played when first learning their instrument!

The sparkling opening of this dramatic overture along with triumphant brass sounds set the stage for an engaging musical journey. Beautiful melodic moments and rhythmic interest will keep musicians and audience engaged from beginning to end. Wonderful!

titre: Pictures at an Exhibition: Promenade III & IV
Pictures at an Exhibition: Gnomus & Promenade

description: Contrasting tempos and timbres propel the excitement in this contrasting and rhythmic work. Particularly demanding for percussionists. Well-suited for contest and festival performances.

This poignant work will provide your band the opportunity to feature expressive ensemble playing with masterful orchestration for interwoven woodwind and brass lines. This newly revised version features an expanded percussion section that tastefully supports the engaging melodies by the woodwinds and brass. A beautifully lyric selection to complement your programs.
titre: Leaves That Descend To No Drum

description: Based on the 19th century Japanese folk song, "Takai-Yama." Lots of melodic and rhythmic vitality for young band. Excellent for multicultural programming.
titre: As I Gaze From The High Mountain

description: This vocally inspired composition is masterfully arranged for concert band by Larry Daehn. Chorale-like melodies within Teleman's style combining the German Protestand Baroque with the lighter Italian and French "style galant" make for a beautiful and expressive work. Lovely!

A striking musical picture of the Goddess of Love; her birth from the foam of the sea, her other-worldly beauty, and her bewitching power over mortal men. From: “Olympus: Four Mythological Legends.” Splendid!

This delightful presentation is based on "Baises Moy" ("Kiss Me,") a French folk tune dating back to the fifteenth centruy. The theme moves through the band as dialogues (antiphonies) between contrsting wind groups. There's a joyful sound of Renasissance pagentry, as layers of various colors play against each other accompanied by lively percussion. A wonderful change of pace within your next performance.

A big, bold American patchwork of “My Country ‘Tis of Thee,” “Yankee Doodle,” “Chester” and “America the Beautiful.” Spacious harmonies and brilliant orchestration abound in this striking patriotic showpiece!

Tribute to America’s folk heritage. This big, colorful masterwork for band combines the familiar tunes “The Shantyman’s Life,” “The Erie Canal,” and “Shoo Fly” into a charming setting of three movements. Perfect for concert or festival use.
Something magical happens when a popular acapella choral work is skillfully arranged for winds. Band music doesn’t get any more beautiful than this. A wonderful addition to band literature.

This might be the very best piece for teaching young bands about 6/8, augmentation, fragmentation, and canon. Based on the most famous sea chantey, "Blow the Man Down." Good tunes for all! A champion among young band music!

A beautiful overture based on the poignant melodies from Max Steiner’s movie score. A true story of a twelve-year-old orphaned son of Scottish immigrants who must find homes for his five younger brothers and sisters on Christmas Day in 1868. Contains an optional “Auld Lang Syne” vocal solo. A touching and epic work!

A grand collection of old British airs and dances masterfully arranged: "Lady Hammond's Alman," "Sellinger's Round," "All in a Garden Green," "The Bashful Swan," "Raggle Taggle Gypsies," and "Three Sea Captains." The sequel to English Country Settings I and II. A real treasure!
sous_titre: Divertimento On Traditional Airs and Dances

description: Originally from a 1911 silent movie, this arrangement is complete with trombone smears, a horse whinny, and lots of fun moments for percussion. Sure to be a concert favorite of bands everywhere!

This exciting band work tells the story of the Great Wall of China. Lots of color and contrast. Dramatic and rhythmic parts for everyone, and superb percussion scoring. Filled with elements young players enjoy and writing that makes them sound good!

A beautiful lyrical piece with a rhythmic current and soaring melody. Hymn-like and stunningly simple. A lovely change-of-pace and way to honor someone while showing the musicality of your ensemble. Stunning!

A great little regimental march filled with good parts for everyone. Titled after the command given to artillery units during the Civil War to have cannons moved into position for battle. Extremely likable!

The powerful opening of Table Rock Festival leads to bright flute solo. Composed in a traditional ABA’ overture form, the serene middle section is surrounded by lively 6/8 sections with a jaunty melody that sticks with the listener. This will complement any concert or festival program.

titre: Pictures at an Exhibition: Promenade III & IV

description: This beautiful lyrical piece is a set of eleven variations built on two eight-measure themes. The burdens of technique and range are gone, so the young player can just concentrate on making beautiful sounds. Music for the Mind, but mostly for the Heart!

A Scottish showpiece for every section of your band! A catchy little trumpet melody is tossed all around the band, accompanied by bustling woodwinds, the sounds of bagpipes, and wild drumming! This happy parade is momentarily interrupted by a bittersweet tune, featuring several band soloists. But the rudimental drums bring everyone back for a big Highland Finale! Hoots Mon!

With its bare fifths at the opening, the rapid harmonic transitions to none-related chords, the modal harmonies, and the majestic ceremonial mood, "Ecce Sacerdos Magnus" is one of Bruckner's most powerful works. Originally a liturgical choral piece, this setting is skillfully arranged for band, so they too may experience the solemnity, mysticism and deep religious feeling of Bruckner's work. Compelling!

The Christmas story is recalled with familiar carols from three countries: Silent Night (Austria), We Three Kings (England), and Sing We Now of Christmas (France). All the colors of Christmas! A holiday favorite!

This wildly hilarious old classic comes to life in this wonderful setting for concert band. Not for the timid! If you have the “animals” in your band (two mallet virtuosos and wind players who “get around” fast and easily in the Key of C) then this piece is for you! The encore extraordinaire!
A fun-filled sunny medley of three well-known tunes: “Mango Walk,” “Tingalayo,” and “Marianne.” Percussion abounds! All the fun and excitement one would expect from this outstanding composer.

Add a touch of 16th and 17th century music to your next performance with this outstanding arrangement by Larry Daehn. This delightful "dance" provides all musicians of the ensemble the opportunity to learn music from the Early Baroque. Splendid!
An intense, driving opening, a bittersweet cantabile and an exciting percussive finale. Lots of energy, vitality and beauty in one composition. Ideal for concert and festival.

The opera “Cavalleria Rusticana” was a burst of Mascagni’s youthful inspiration, and contains the most passionate music he would ever write! This masterful setting is based on the eloquent “Easter Hymn.” Absolutely beautiful!

Short melodic motives coupled with the use of multiple keyboard instruments and piano characterize this "neo-Impressionism" style as realized by composer Jack Stamp. The narration, based on the anonymous poem, is optional. A unique and powerful work!
sous_titre: Do Not Stand At My Grave and Weep

description: A gorgeous work, combining the genius of Ralph Vaughan Williams with all the pomp and nobility is loved in the music of Britain. Programmable for commencement or anytime! Beautiful!
sous_titre: Two Hymns By Ralph Vaughan Williams

description: This robust little march portrays the natural beauty of Alabama’s Cahaba River with references to its Native American history. Catchy melodies and a pleasing combination of major and minor tonalities. An absolute winner for young band!
This brilliant music evokes a river’s beauty, its wildlife, and it’s becoming great torrents of sight, sound and energy spilling over with exhilaration. Breathtakingly beautiful!

The glory of St. Mark’s Cathedral in 17th Century Venice comes alive in this austere setting for winds. Magnificent antiphonal chords and passionate suspensions abound in this elegant Baroque work. A wonderful experience for performers and audience. Awe-inspiring!

This popular overture far outlived the comic opera for which it was written. A popular staple in orchestral repertoire, this delightful arrangement is a welcome addition to the wind band library of encore bon-bons.

This exciting work reveals the image of reaching "Critical Speed" through a constant, underlying rhythmic momentum, which builds in several phrases, growing to a peak of intensity. The music then becomes sheer fun. Very playful and exciting!

This sensitive composition is about emotions that are difficult to verbalize, but that can be expressed with music. It is a beautiful, gentle lullaby inspired by a father putting a newborn child to sleep in the wee hours of the night, but the strength of the climax represents the depth of a parent's feelings. Perfect for that touching moment in any performance!

A hoot, a holler and a hoedown! A top-notch collection of tunes: “The Girl I Left Behind Me,” “The Chisholm Trail,” “The Cowboy,” “Buffalo Gals,” “Golden Slippers,” “Soldier’s Joy,” and “Skip to My Lou.” The best cowboy medley ever! Lots of fun! Movements: I. Chisholm Trail (2:15) II. The Cowboy (4:09) III. At a Cowboy Dance (2:59)
This wonderful march will delight your audiences and performers alike. Standard A, B, Trio march form. Very playable and a perfect addition to your next concert or festival performance.
Based on the18th century Scottish folksong, “In April, When Primroses Paint the Sweet Prairie.” Beautiful lyrical music for all.
This piece takes its title from an Irish jig of the same name. The melody is here set as a waltz and therefore prents itself much less forthrightly than O'Neill's original tune. A delight!

One of the most famous fugues from Bach’s final Magnum Opus. The beautiful D minor theme first appears simply in the four voices of a woodwind quartet—flute, oboe, clarinet and bassoon—and then draws upon all the instrumental colors and textures to build an ever more dramatic and powerful mosaic of the band’s voices. A masterwork transcribed masterfully!

This masterwork open with one of Handel’s most gorgeous Largos. Then it springs into a breathtaking whirlwind of instrumental bravura! A captivating little "musical clockwork" theme is deftly tossed to every section with lightning speed! A classical wind band showcase!

This piece is full of youthful exuberance! Based on the last movement of a concerto written about 1713.  This is a big exciting organ work for band. Two groups playng sixteenth notes; groups playing eighth notes, adding excitement; and the quarter-note octave melodies, speaking the powerful bass-pipes voice. A wonderful experience for performers and audiences alike!

This original work is dedicated to young trumpet players everywhere, in tribute to their talent and enthusiasm. "Concert Piece for Trumpet and Band" conatins various styles cast in a single movement unified by a fanfare figure which begins the work and reappears at important places later in the piece. Plenty of opportunity to showcase that special player without overtaxing the ensemble. Wonderful!
titre: Concert Piece For Trumpet and Band

description: This magnificent work, based on tunes from Cecil Sharp’s One Hundred English Folksongs, includes the haunting Farewell, Nancy, the jaunty The Sign of the Bonny Blue and the march-like Laidy Maisry. Stunningly beautiful!

This beautiful arrangement for winds and percussion is based on “The Minstrel Boy” (words by Thomas Moore set to The Moreen¬, an old Irish air.) Opportunities abound for a band to show beauty and expressiveness within this work. Breathtaking!

Using the traditional folk tunes, “The Blackberry Blossom” and “The Girl I Left Behind Me,” Sir Hamilton Harty painted a charming picture of turn-of-the-century life in rural Northern Ireland. This brilliant concert band setting captures all the sparkle and wit of the original. An Irish treasure!

This little march has everything! A jaunty first strain, a driving second strain with great low brass countermelodies, a noble trio, and a martial breakstrain! A top-notch crowd pleaser for young bands!

Experience all the drama and terror of Goethe’s poem and Schubert’s score—the wild ride of the boy and his father through the stormy night, assailed by the dreaded Erl-King—in this exciting new setting for concert band. Treat your band and audience to the Sturm und Drang of this pulsating, driving Classic!

Jack Stamp's "Ere the World Began to Be" is based on a 13th century plainchant, "Divinum Myusterium." A varitey of compositional techniques, not frequently associated with literature at this level, provide a uniqe and interesting pedagogical experience. Spellbinding!
titre: Ere The World Began To Be

description: A charming collection of contrasts: royal pageantry, wistful tranquility and raucous fun! Your band and audience will love this jolly trip to London! Movements: I. Buckingham Palace (1:19) II. St. Paul’s Cathedral (2:15) III. Piccadilly Circus (1:20)

This colorful setting of May Day Carol, O Waly Waly, and The Ash Grove will delight players and audiences. Although arranged as a one-movement work, the settings may be performed separately. The serenade, in particular, would be a suitable contest selection where a moderate tempo and quiet ending are needed to offer a balanced program. A wonderful and versatile addition to your music library!
sous_titre: Serenade and Jig On English Folksongs

description: Exciting sensuous melodies over infectious Spanish two-against-three rhythms. Dramatic, powerful percussion. A surefire winner!
A wonderfully arranged collection of early English Country songs. Movement 1: Early One Morning Movement 2: Lavender's Blue Movement 3: Davy, Davy Kick Knack Delightful!

Your band will have as much fun playing this piece as the composer had writing it! A great tune for your young band’s funny bone! (How many pieces ask your drummers to make “Quack-Quack” sounds?) Pure entertainment!
Based on the 19th century Japanese folk song, "Takai-Yama." Lots of melodic and rhythmic vitality for young band. Excellent for multicultural programming.
titre: As I Gaze From The High Mountain

description: Feature your first chair player or whole trombone section on this happy little gem! You can even get your xylophone players involved! A real treat and great fun for everyone!
sous_titre: After The 1913 Happy Rag By R. G. Grady

description: An outstanding medley of three well-known Handel works: “Air and Variations,” “Thanks Be to Thee,” and “See! The Conquering Hero Comes.” A great way to introduce your players to Handel and the Baroque period. First-rate music!

“Green Bushes” was one of the best known country-side folksongs in England. Grainger accumulated at least ten variations of this song (also known as “Lost Lady Found” and “The Three Gipsies.”) This arrangement is based on his 1921 revision. Performers and audiences love this delightful dance!

This magnificent score is dedicated to the Old West! A grand piece based on traditional cowboy and Western folk tunes: “Home on the Range,” “The Dying Cowboy,” “The Ballad of Billy the Kid,” “The Streets of Laredo,” “The Days of ‘49,” and “The California Stage Company.” A big mix of beauty and fun!

A charming symphonic march based on an 18th Century nursery rhyme and folk tune - probably a parody of British nobility. A happy regimental tune marches through several jolly transformations before the duke and his men stride off into the distance. Great fun!
titre: The Grand Old Duke Of York

description: Plenty of Medieval pageantry and drama. A rhythmically vibrant dance tune in minor mode permeates this colorful band score. Young band music of the highest order!
A big, bold, beautiful overture! This piece has excitement, nobility and heart! A walloping showpiece for concert and festival!

Treat your players and audience to music of a bygone era—music that accompanied acrobats, wild animals and clowns. This dandy march-galop can be performed as a street march, a brisk march, or as a rip-roarin’ gallop. Whichever tempo you decide on, this music is fun!

Lots of color and contrast in this masterpiece. A gathering of three old spirituals: “Brethren, We Have Met to Worship,” the familiar “Shall We gather at the River” and the exultant “A Great Camp-Meeting in the Promised Land!” Inspiring!
From it's mysterious opening, through the beautiful lyrical middle section and concluding with a bold, energetic ending; this work will have your audiences captivated from start to finish.

This tune from La Gioconda is one of the most famous ballet pieces ever written, used by everyone from Walt Disney, Spike Jones and Allan Sherman to Mel Brooks, Garfield and The Simpsons. Treat your audience to this two-minute Italian roller-coaster ride! Encore!
This brilliant music evokes a river’s beauty, its wildlife, and it’s becoming great torrents of sight, sound and energy spilling over with exhilaration. Breathtakingly beautiful!

This magnificent work, based on tunes from Cecil Sharp’s One Hundred English Folksongs, includes the haunting Farewell, Nancy, the jaunty The Sign of the Bonny Blue and the march-like Laidy Maisry. Stunningly beautiful!
Three Irish tunes artfully scored for winds and percussion. Wonderful contrast: a gorgeous slow movement and two breath-taking dances! A sure-to-please showpiece! Movements: I. Reel II. Ayre III. Jig

The lovely old tune on which this composition is based is know by a variety of names: "Farewell! But Whenever You Welcome the Hour," "To Rodney We Will Go," and "Moll Roone." The "Andante e rubato" used from the outset of the piece, gives conductors as much freedom as they might desire. Wonderful lyrical writing and a beautiful tribute to that special someone.

A wonderful portrait of Abraham Lincoln and the Civil War. The words ‘Now he belongs to the ages,’ spoken at the death of Abraham Lincoln, is the basis for this musical tribute. Bold with beautiful wistful melodies, fragments of “Battle Hymn of the Republic” and “Dixie,” and dramatic percussion scoring make this an inspired and memorable achievement.

The big, brassy syncopated opening tells us something great is coming, and “Integritas” does not disappoint! A fast-driving “big tune” with an Adagio Cantabile section featuring beautiful solos for flute, oboe, trumpet, horn and trombone. All players are back for an “over-the-top” Finale. A noble concert opener or closer that shouts, “Integrity!”

A suite of old French folksongs cleverly arranged for concert band. A wonderful combination of children’s games, love songs, troubadour’s tunes, court music and rollicking songs for the King’s Ryoal Hunt. A real masterwork! Movements: I. Le Furet  II. The Laurel Grove III. King Dagobert
titre: In The Forest Of The King

description: Beautiful wind instrument colors abound in this stately masterpiece. Written for piano in 1883, A L’Église (In the Church) has been lovingly arranged for wind band. Gorgeous!

An exciting take-off flight for any concert! This piece truly soars as every player adds their voice in this joyful tribute to following hopes and dreams! Inspired by Helen Keller’s quote: “One can never consent to creep when one feels an impulse to soar.” Breathtaking!

In 1906, Ralph Vaughan Williams, editor of the English Hymnal, asked his friend and colleague, Gustav Holst, to write these hymns. This work combines the melodies in a richly-colored concert setting of fanfare, canon, chorale and processional. A noble Holst tribute!
Chant-like textures of the Russian Orthodox Church are infused with Rachmaninoff’s incomparable melodies. Exquisite music beautifully arranged for winds!

A driving animated piece that describes the random intensity and violence of a storm. The middle section, the “eye” of the storm, is a peaceful contrast. A very exciting piece, and a favorite of young players!

This tempestuous little piece became a favorite of many bands during the Civil War. Often compared to Von Suppe’s “Poet and Peasant” Overture, this piece is a tour de force on any concert program. Give your players and audience the happy occasion to shout “Hurrah!”

The glory of St. Mark’s Cathedral in 17th Century Venice comes alive in this austere setting for winds. Magnificent antiphonal chords and passionate suspensions abound in this elegant Baroque work. A wonderful experience for performers and audience. Awe-inspiring!

This beautiful arrangement for winds and percussion is based on “The Minstrel Boy” (words by Thomas Moore set to The Moreen¬, an old Irish air.) Opportunities abound for a band to show beauty and expressiveness within this work. Breathtaking!

Courtly pageantry, simple beauty and rambunctious fun abound in this wonderful setting! A delightful suite of “Mr. Purcell”s Riggadoon.” “Over the Hills and Far Away,” and “Lazy Pirate’s Jig.” Music to delight the king, the commoner and everyone else!

Austere, powerful music of England’s most famous Baroque composer. From the first sounds of the muffled drums, your players and audience will be taken back to a snowy London morning in 1685 for the funeral procession of Queen Mary II. Spellbinding!
titre: Music For The Funeral Of Queen Mary

description: Filled with imagery, this beautiful descriptive work will captivate musicians and audiences. Breathtaking!

The Dignified Minuet and the rollicking "Champagne" Aria (from the sublime to the riotous) are joined in this charming little medley from one of the world's most famous operas. A happy way to introduce your band to Mozart. Alluring and delightful!
titre: Minuet and Presto From Don Giovanni

description: Two Ukrainian folk tunes; “Minka” and “The Birch Tree,” combined with sleigh bells, tambourines and wood blocks to take us on a snowy Russian sleigh ride. Everyone gets the melody in this delightful young band piece. Everyone will be humming or whistling the infentious “Minka” tune! Adventuresome fun!
This bright work is a celebratory overture based on a three-note motive. This unique “In Memory” piece is truly a celebration of life

This magnificent piece is based on the “Sine Nomine” melody of Ralph Vaughan Williams. Brilliant fanfares and grand sonorous melodies come pouring out of this powerful work. A stunning addition to any concert.
Incoporate a little Greek Mythology into the band curriculum with this bold and descriptive work for young bands.

This work was composed in tribute to, and in memory of, the youngest person ever to receive the Medal of Honor, Jack Lucas. A very noble and dramatic work with a brief, slightly aleatoric section giving several snare drummers— at least four—the opportunity to invent their own part for the ten-second ‘war’ section. A real ‘grownup’ piece for young band!

This British folk song setting is based on two traditional English folksongs: "The Old Woman and the Peddler," and "The Country Farmer's Son."  A great way to introduce performers to alla breve and a delightful change of pace for any performance!
titre: A March On The King's Highway

description: Ready the ships! This work captures all the excitement and beauty of long ago journeys of the tall ships. Full of happy "swashbuckling" melodies, grand orchestral flourishes and colorful splashes of mallet percussion. Band, ahoy!
A fine old Italian-American March, in the style of a tarantella. Bright, breezy, and a lot of fun!
Powerful harmonies and rhythms paint a vivid picture of Pegasus, his young master, Bellerophon, and the dreaded monster, Chimaera. A wonderful adventure for young band!

This beautiful sorrowful Bach melody appears in his Contata No. 12 and again in the Crucifixus of his Mass in B Minor. Every voice and every part contribute to the success of this work's message. A wonderful piece for teaching good tone and phrasing, and a great way to bring the beauty of Bach into your classroom.

An excellent regimental march that will put you in the reviewing stand, watching a favorite band marching by. Drums in the distance. They're coming! Now there’re right in front of us! Playing that splendid tune! Terrific!
One can just imagine the bands or armies meeting at dawn and signaling to one another in this stunning work. Great melodies for everyone. Very attractive!
Lots of color and contrast in this exciting journey through a wonderland of delightful variations. Every section has the opportunity to shine! A famous melody with a creative touch. Engaging!

Mysterious voices emanate from silence, followed by bold themes, flashes of dialogue between winds and percussion, and a fiery recapitulation. Awe and drama is captured in this great adventure for young bands!

This composition was written to give young bands a positive experience with intense and driving rhythms. Right from the first note, the level of spirit and intensity is high! An amazing experience for all!
Grand, heroic melodies and brilliant fanfares punctuated by intrepid rhythms. This inspired composition was dedicated to a special music educator. An ideal showpiece for concert of festival!
A slow, resplendent statement of the folksong is followed by a boisterous “hit the trail” section. Another outstanding setting for young band. Sure to please!
Based on “Kitty Tyrell,” an Irish air of the mid-eighteenth century. A chance for all instruments to show their tonal warmth and beauty. This is a perfect study in expressive playing for young bands.
An emotion-filled odyssey for the mature band. Full of expressive and stirring musical moments. Astonishingly breathtaking.
Feature your first chair player or whole trombone section on this happy little gem! You can even get your xylophone players involved! A real treat and great fun for everyone!
sous_titre: After The 1913 Happy Rag By R. G. Grady

description: Festive brass fanfares announce this magnificent combination of Beethoven’s “Ode to Joy” with the famous carol, “O Come All Ye Faithful.” Nobility abounds in this fantasy on two famous beloved melodies. Sure to be a holiday favorite!
sous_titre: Ode To Joy - O Come All Ye Faithful

description: Based on an old Highland dance tune, "Carron's Reel," also known as "Gentry Libby." The dance tune and an original tune are played over a bagpipe effect with regimental drums, first approaching, and then passing into the distace. Wonderful!
A light and lively, ragtime work to feature an alto saxophone soloist with concert band. Fun!

This famous courtly dance is an early Handel work. A relatively easy and profoundly beautiful composition full of nobility and drama. A Wonderful way to acquaint your band with Handel and the Baroque!

From the slow, deliberate Cossack-dance beginning, through a series of ever-quickening tunes, to a breathless prestissimo and topped off with a shouted "Hey!" This little medley of Ukrainian dances will be a sure-fire crowd pleaser! Lots of fun!

A powerful dedicatory theme of brass and percussion opens this brilliant tribute to the magnificent granite monument in South Dakota, and the music builds from start to finish. Harmonic and rhythmic excitement abound in this patriotic showpiece for young musicians.
A lively little jig melody dances throughout, mixing with many other British folk tunes. A delightful, non-stop band showpiece!

This contemporary sounding concert march is a solid choice for any performance situation! A bright tempo, brass fanfares, fresh harmonies, and driving percussion all contribute to this stirring music. Flowing lyrical lines are punctuated by florid woodwind garnishes. A stately trio section offers a shift in colors, followed by an exciting breakstrain, and a powerful final strain that will thrill audiences. An

This period work is a setting of three short movements based on German pieces of the very early Seventeenth Century.  I. Antiphonal Song based on "O filii et finliae" by Leisring II. Courtly Dance, "Agatha" by Widmann III. Royal Banquet Music by Schein A wonderful way to introduce performers and audiences to movement works and music of the Renaissance.

A beautiful "In Memoriam" piece reminiscent of the composer’s "A Song for Friends." A gorgeous 3/4 melody emerges from the low voices, is joined by an ethereal woodwind choir, develops into a majestic, noble utterance, and then fades into quietness. A tender piece to remember someone in your school or community. Touching and beautiful!

A fetching little melody over a first-rate snare drum rhythm in a very attractive patrol-style march. Written to honor the men and boys of the Civil War – North and South. Fun to play and fun to listen to! Wonderful!

A unique arrangement combining the very gentle song with a boisterous dance. This setting has several sections:  -Introduction  -Suogan Theme with variations  -Percussion Transition  -Original Jig theme with variations  -The Jig and Suogan themes together  -Coda Interesting and delightful for everyone!
From the courtly trumpet fanfare to the big stately Trio, this march says nobility! Imperial themes and impressive countermelodies abound! Gorgeous horn parts. Thrilling and very attractive!

Four very attractive French songs combined to make a great work for concert or festival. While each tune is strong enough to stand alone, they each have interesting stories that make them wonderful teaching material. Memorable music from long ago!  Movements: 1. The Duke of Marlborough Goes to War 2. Chanson Triste (Une Jeune Fillette) 3. Bon Voyage, Monsieur Dumollet 4. Petit Papa

A great descriptive suite with outstanding original music interspersed with old tunes: “Lovely Vine,” “Endless Day,” “Riflemen of Bennington” and “Chester.” Brimming with variety—from the quiet beauty of falling snow to the happy sounds of marching soldiers. A masterwork!

A bold mixture of early Spanish plainsong, 14th Century organum chords and zealous percussion. This variations on a 1399 monastery song highlights every section of your band. A perfect choice for festival or concert. Lots of beauty and drama!

A splendid portrait of the Scottish Highlands packed with lots of wonderful musical moments. The beautiful variations of Loch Lomond combined with lush chords, magnificent horn melodies, alto saxophone (or bagpipe) solos, crisp regimental snare drumming, and clever features for flute-piccolo and xylophone make this work absolutely stunning!

From the beginning rhythmic eighth notes to the driving Coda, this piece never stops! And talk about an infectious melody – you will hear this little Aeolian tune sung and whistled around your band room long after rehearsal! There is a lot of spirit and a lot of dance in this sprightly piece which appeals to the “inner spirit” in all of us!
Take flight with this exhilarating, bright, and radiant piece featuring exciting parts for everyone; every tone color imaginable and gargantuan percussion! Celebratory and Shining!

A wonderful tribute to American folksong featuring Nineteenth century farm songs, sweetheart songs and silly songs—all affectionately combined in a grand love letter to America! A great cross curricular opportunity, as well! Delightful!

The song itself is a 32-bar popular song form. The first variation subjects the gentle song to some fragmentation and varied harmonies, while the second variation turns the song into ragtime. Captivating!

The compelling five-note melody is passed throughout the band over exciting Native American drumming. Based on an Ojibwe ceremonial song, this almost-hypnotic little melody will capture the imaginations of your players and audience!

Based on an ancient song of the Isle of Islay, "Song of the Hebrides" is a beautiful piece of music. It is also a fine piece for introducing or discussing music of the Scottish islands, simple AB song form, melodic-harmonic balance, musical phrase, suspension-resolution and general music vocabulary. Wonderul!
A lyrical selection young players will enjoy. Modest ranges, flowing lines, modern harmonies and a strong melody for all. A perfect piece for the young band.

A unique composition for young bands that encourages players to focus on making beautiful music together by providing a lovely melody, uncomplicated rhythms and smooth harmonies. A simple, moving tribute to friendship! Impressive!

This arrangement is based on the "Sonata in D Minor, W. 64/24" for keyboard composed by Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach in the mid-18th century. An excellent work for introducing young musicians to the innovations of C.P.E. Bach's music.

Courtly pageantry, simple beauty and rambunctious fun abound in this wonderful setting! A delightful suite of “Mr. Purcell”s Riggadoon.” “Over the Hills and Far Away,” and “Lazy Pirate’s Jig.” Music to delight the king, the commoner and everyone else!
Energy, excitement and drama abound is this powerful, driving masterwork. A joyful showpiece!
A delightful romp through bygone British music halls and salons. A rare old one-step artfully arranged. Lots of fun!

Berlioz's “Grande Symphonie Funebre et Triomphale” (for 200 winds and percussion,) scored for concert band. Brilliant brass fanfares, big noble melodies and antiphonal percussion make this piece the high point of any performance. A Perfect choice for festival or honor band finale.

Like all of Deiro's overtures, "Trieste" is in the style of Rossini's operatic overtures. A forceful, dramatic opening is followed by a warm bel canto melody then bounds into a series of opera buffa melodies, with dazzling bravura parts for everyone, even a rousing basso profundo for the bottom of the band. A brand-new festive melody, a breathtaking coda, and a dramatic maestoso restatement of the opening theme bring
This high-stepping quickstep will bring smiles to your audience. Everyone will enjoy this lively tune that was all the rage, on both sides of the Atlantic, in 1911. Great fun!

Teaching 6/8 rhythm has never been so much fun with one of the most familiar TV theme songs of all time! This little march will delight your band and bring a big smile to your audience as you take them back to Mayfield—to Ward and June, Wally and Beaver, Eddie, Lumpy, Whitey and Larry. Pure fun!
An exciting showpiece for band! Great opener—or closer—for your next concert. Lots of color and excitement. Grand proclamations from many sections in this great work!
Written in the style of a U. S. Civil War marching song, this captivating little march features the historic flag-raising bugle call, “To the Colors.” Delightful!

All the drama, excitement and color that we expect from this gifted composer predicated on non-harmonic passing tones. This advancing-changing-evolving piece recalls a quote from Marcus Aurelius: “Time is a sort of river of passing events, and strong is its current.” Stunning!

One of the most popular, and the noisiest, of all of Strauss’ dance pieces. “Unter Donner und Blitz” evokes the sound of thunder and lightning through incessant timpani rolls, cymbal clashes and bass drum thunder claps. This sparkling new arrangement is sure to prompt—what else—thunderous applause!

There is a lot of variety and contrast compressed into this work for young band. Instrumental colors suggest moods from declamatory to foreboding to playful; textures range from sostenuto to staccato. An excellent opportunity to invite your students to invent story lines or scenarios to be shared with your audience.
Featuring "Blackamwore by the Stour", "The Winter's Willow," and "Boy Johnny."
A fine old Italian-American March, in the style of a tarantella. Bright, breezy, and a lot of fun!

Festive brass fanfares announce this magnificent combination of Beethoven’s “Ode to Joy” with the famous carol, “O Come All Ye Faithful.” Nobility abounds in this fantasy on two famous beloved melodies. Sure to be a holiday favorite!
sous_titre: Ode To Joy - O Come All Ye Faithful

description: A unique arrangement combining the very gentle song with a boisterous dance. This setting has several sections:  -Introduction  -Suogan Theme with variations  -Percussion Transition  -Original Jig theme with variations  -The Jig and Suogan themes together  -Coda Interesting and delightful for everyone!
Achievement is a chorale and march using the first 7 notes found in most beginning band methods.
Name That Christmas Carol, which uses only 6 notes from concert Bb to G, is designed to be an audience participation game that will add some fun to your first Christmas concert.

The beginning tempo marking says it all for this exciting piece: “With energy and determination.” The strength of Zephyrus and the rhythm of his “Z” (Morse Code rhythm: long-long-short-short) are the foundation of this bold, dramatic work for young band.

A musical depiction of two Arkansas towns devastated by a tornado. The story is told, moving from quietness to havoc, and incorporating the beautiful old hymn, “What Wondrous Love Is This.” A grand synthesis of beauty, drama and the aleatoric. Memorable!

A musical fantasy depicting the wide range of the wind’s character that occurs throughout the year. Opening with a gentle breeze followed by clouds, thunder, lightning and rain. From beautiful little melodies of the lonesome prairie to big, brash percussive storm sounds; there are a lot of opportunities to study contrast. Brilliant and accessible!

“Whispering,” first made popular by Whiteman, and later, by Goodman and Dorsey, is the basis for this fun-filled arrangement. This band-friendly, kid-friendly piece will ‘fox-trot’ your young players back to America’s big band era. Entertaining!
Poignant and hauntingly beautiful. This lyrical piece is a touching memorial to help heal and remember. Breathtaking.

This is a perfect study for expressive playing with young bands. A chance for all instruments to show their warmth and beauty. Based on “Gwenith Gwyn,” a bittersweet eighteenth century Welsh folksong. Beautiful and illuminating!
titre: While I Watch The Yellow Wheat

description: Exquisite melodies soar throughout this touching masterwork for winds! Beautiful music brilliantly scored! Breathtaking.

The sounds of the Old West come alive! This work portrays the lives of the pioneers who sought to find a better way of life for their families and those who would follow them. Full of style, energy, beauty, and character! Very enjoyable!

A Stirring, Noble march in the traditional regimental style. Commissioned by the United States Military Academy Band. Dedicated to the Academy’s motto, “Duty, Honor, Country”, and to West Point’s two hundred years of patriotic service. Very inspirational!

Based on an old Highland dance tune, "Carron's Reel," also known as "Gentry Libby." The dance tune and an original tune are played over a bagpipe effect with regimental drums, first approaching, and then passing into the distace. Wonderful!
From the courtly trumpet fanfare to the big stately Trio, this march says nobility! Imperial themes and impressive countermelodies abound! Gorgeous horn parts. Thrilling and very attractive!

Christmas Stomp is a perfect composition for a beginning band’s Christmas Concert. It features three percussion soloists that play on different sounding buckets. The piece is written in a swing style, which will make it more enjoyable to play.

The Johannes Brahms Symphony No. 1 Theme is designed to give your best players an opportunity to play a solo with band accompaniment. This solo is the same one that appears on page 36, book 1 of The Yamaha Advantage® for oboe, bassoon, alto clarinet, tenor saxophone and horn. This arrangement also includes solo parts for Flute, Clarinet and Alto Saxophone. This piece can also be performed by band alone.

Elite March is written to introduce the march form and style to young musicians. Playing marches is part of the heritage of the band and is an importance style that students should learn to play. The form of this composition includes the traditional modulation to the subdominant at the Trio.

Snarendipity features solo snare drum with band. This piece can be performed by one snare drummer or with multiple snare drum soloists. The snare drum part includes contemporary sounds as well as many rudiments.
Legends is designed to reinforce eighth-note patterns and 3/4 time. The composition is a perfect contest/festival style piece and as the title implies, is reminiscent of swashbuckling heroes.

Rock America opens with a full band lyrical statement of America the Beautiful leading to a restatement of America the Beautiful in a hip new style reminiscent of the great Ray Charles version. The arrangement includes You’re a Grand Old Flag, which has elements of the rock feel, interspersed with a traditional march style.

Christmas Gloria begins with a snare drum solo snares off which sets the tone for a bolero style arrangement reminiscent of the Little Drummer Boy but based on the all time favorite Pat-a-Pan. The arrangement builds to a climax that brings in the melody of the Gloria section of Angles We Have Heard On High.
Honor March is written to introduce the March form and style to young musicians. Playing marches is part of the heritage of the band and is an importance style that the students should learn to play.

The Ash Grove is designed to give your best trumpet, trombone, baritone or tuba player an opportunity to play a solo with band accompaniment. It should serve as the culmination of study for the soloist at the completion of any method book 1. The piece also has all of the solo material cued in the band so if a soloist is not available you can perform this piece with band alone.

Christmas Surprise is a perfect composition for your first Christmas Concert. It only uses the first 7 notes introduced in most beginning band methods; concert Bb to G plus the low A. This arrangement uniquely combines Jingle Bells and Jolly Old Saint Nicholas with Haydn’s Surprise Symphony. It also includes a unique section where the band sings.
Sentinel is designed to reinforce the key of Eb after the note concert Ab is learned. It contains contemporary harmonies, tuneful melodies and exciting percussion.

Christmas Toyland is a clever new arrangement that combines the famous march from the Tchaikovsky Nutcracker with the Victor Herbert classic Toyland. It is perfect to reinforce triplets and 3/4 time. The combination of these two wonderful compositions is certain to be an audience favorite.

Outback Rhapsody introduces the delightful music of Australia in a contest style piece. It is perfect to reinforce 6/8 time in 2. It combines 3 popular folk songs from Australia and would be great to use in a multicultural presentation.

Antiphony is a serious composition that will highlight your budding percussionists. This bold and harmonically progressive piece has an extensive percussion section that is placed antiphonally around the band to give the piece a stereophonic effect.

Four very attractive French songs combined to make a great work for concert or festival. While each tune is strong enough to stand alone, they each have interesting stories that make them wonderful teaching material. Memorable music from long ago!  Movements: 1. The Duke of Marlborough Goes to War 2. Chanson Triste (Une Jeune Fillette) 3. Bon Voyage, Monsieur Dumollet 4. Petit Papa
Energy, excitement and drama abound is this powerful, driving masterwork. A joyful showpiece!
Here's an easy and tuneful blues number that you'll enjoy programming year after year! Expertly scored for beginning bands, this piece gives you the opportunity to teach the concept of "swing."
Powerful melodic lines and an interesting modal flavor are features of this exciting march. An ideal choice for that important first concert.
The relaxed spirit of the islands is captured in this colorful number which effectively features your entire flute section.
Strong melodic lines accompanied by short quarter notes will have your band sounding their best in no time! Perfect for that first performance.
Yep, you guessed it! "Three Blind Mice" entertainingly arranged in a dynamic rock style. Expertly scored for bands just starting out.
Here's a fantastic march that's perfect for first year bands. All sections of the band get a chance with the melody.

This concert march is solidly scored and incorporates the "call and response" compositional technique similar to that used by composers in the Baroque period. All sections of the band get a chance to play the melody. Ideal for that important first performance.
Young players will really enjoy this tuneful calypso. Easy repetitive rhythms make it a breeze to perform.

A fun and creative composition designed to reinforce 6/8 compound meter. Interesting harmonies and an eerie mood will pique the interest and imaginations of your students and audiences alike. A very enjoyable musical experience to enhance the musicianship of your students!
titre: A Ride Through The Haunted Mansion

description: The essence of improving the aural skills of your students is by teaching them to recognize melodic intervals as part of the structure of music. This contest/festival style piece is also designed to teach most of the major and minor melodic intervals through the two main themes of the piece. As an added bonus, the back page of the parts includes both of the melodies written out for all of the instruments so that you

A true "contest" style piece for the beginning band that uses limited note and rhythm resources, but is very creatively written. Your youngest students will feel like they are playing serious music, as the piece is bold, aggressive and sounds more difficult than it plays. This is the type of exceptional music you have come to expect from two of the most popular composers of beginning band music. This piece is
Shaker Settings is a combination of two shaker songs Father James’s Song and the famous Simple Gifts. This is a very playable and effective arrangement for contest use.

Equinox is a tour-de-force for the young band and can serve as the culmination of study at the end of The Yamaha Advantage Band Method book 2 or any band method book 2. It is a contest piece with driving rhythms, bold fanfare gestures, lyrical lines and climatic moments that will help to show off your band to their best abilities.

Genesis is a contest style piece that can be used as the culmination of study at the end of The Yamaha Advantage or at the end of any band method book 1. This popular performance piece from the back of book 1 has been requested by directors to be available separately so that they can perform the piece at contest. It is a real winner!
This stately, evocative arrangement is based upon an ancient Native American hymn. A very effective choice for your next program.
Revive the "Spirit of '76" with this driving and dramatic march by Ralph Gingery. Excellent!
Jay Chattaway's stirring and beautiful work was written as a tribute to a young musician. It's a perfect piece for developing bands!
This lively Latin-flavored original captures both the spirit and excitement of the islands. A high-energy piece that is lots of fun to perform. It will be a winner with the audience as well!

Jeff Taylor has taken the ever-popular Irving Berlin standard and given it a most creative treatment including a swing-march, dixieland style, 6/8 march, and driving big-band swing. You really can't miss with this fine arrangement!
A unique way to feature a drum set soloist with the concert band. This Jay Chattaway original, with its straight ahead jazz feel, will be a program favorite!

This dynamic piece starts with a marcato, strongly rhythmic character with lots of fine percussion writing. The contrasting middle section features tuneful themes with several meter changes for added interest.

Bob James' masterful adaptation of Bizet's dance suite features fiery rhythms and exquisite colors in a superb contemporary setting. This energetic arrangement is certain to be a favorite on any program.
Here's a pop-styled piece designed to spotlight your entire flute section. Several effective and contrasting moods are presented in this delightful original.
Once you've heard this electrifying journey into the day's pop and rock sounds, you'll definitely want it to highlight your next program!
All the excitement and sophistication of the Bob James recording has been captured in this outstanding arrangement.
This contemporary pop-styled ballad spotlights a flugelhorn (trumpet) soloist and will round out your concert program beautifully.

This excellent overture was written for the TCU Wind Ensemble. Heroic in character, the piece masterfully exploits the variety of colors available to the modern wind ensemble through interesting solis and solos. This piece is tonal in nature and contains many original and identifiable themes.

A dramatic arrangement of favorite Christmas themes in the masterful Jay Chattaway style.  Featuring "What Child Is This?" and a jazzy feeling contempory setting of "Jingle Bells."  You'll enjoy performing this brilliant showpiece for many years to come!

From its ceremonial introduction to its powerful conclusion, the masterful thematic delineation and development of "Ritual Celebration" are central to this major work for symphonic band.  Based upon the Kyrie from the Gregorian Mass "In Festis Duplicibus."

A powerful one-movement composition based upon several musical motives that are skillfully developed into a piece that explores many of the varied tonal and rhythmic resources of today's wind ensemble. Great for contest or concert use!
Achievement is a chorale and march using the first 7 notes found in most beginning band methods.

Christmas Stomp is a perfect composition for a beginning band’s Christmas Concert. It features three percussion soloists that play on different sounding buckets. The piece is written in a swing style, which will make it more enjoyable to play.
The seasonal favorite "O, Tannenbaum" effectively presented in a series of jazzy variations. A sure-fire crowd pleaser!
A remarkably fine choice for contest use. This overture features dramatic, contrasting themes with real musical impact.
Here's a rock chart with a powerful and very contemporary feel. Guaranteed to be a major hit on any program!
This outstanding trumpet duet has a distinctive Spanish flavor. The lively, rhythmic theme is contrasted by a lyrical middle section. An excellent feature for your top trumpet players.

Although technically within the range of most intermediate bands, City Of Champions sounds incredibly mature! Contrasting moods, skillful interplay of themes and lots of bold ensemble power make it a clear winner!
This enchanting lyrical composition spotlights your alto saxophone soloist. Note the very effective cadenza section.
POWER DRIVE captures the spirit of today's popular music. All section of the band have interesting parts in this exciting and very enjoyable selection.
SEASCAPE is a wonderful tone poem for band which describes the serenity and beauty of a coastal scene. Very effective!

Owen Glendower led a Welsh uprising against England in the 16th century. Though his quest for independence was unsuccessful, he is none-the-less regarded as a national hero. The overture's heroic and dramatic nature makes it an outstanding choice for any program.
This brilliant concert march has it all: powerful themes, effective counterlines, dramatic contrasts and plenty of good solid scoring. Very effective!

Here's a great arrangement of a lively folk song from the "outback" by one of Australia's leading composer-arrangers. Right down to the hand clapping and foot stomping, your band and audiences will love this energetic piece!

Jay Chattaway's unique talent for writing music that makes young players sound mature is most evident in this fine composition. The tuneful, British character make this a natural choice for exciting programming.
This composition lets you feature one of your often "unsung" players in lyrical and animated styles. The solo part may be played by baritone, trombone, tenor sax or bassoon. Superb!

George M. Cohan's patriotic standard has long been a crowd favorite and it's made even more exciting in this skillful and inventive arrangement! All sections of the band have interesting parts in this very enjoyable and lively selection.

The Johannes Brahms Symphony No. 1 Theme is designed to give your best players an opportunity to play a solo with band accompaniment. This solo is the same one that appears on page 36, book 1 of The Yamaha Advantage® for oboe, bassoon, alto clarinet, tenor saxophone and horn. This arrangement also includes solo parts for Flute, Clarinet and Alto Saxophone. This piece can also be performed by band alone.
Here's an easy and tuneful blues number that you'll enjoy programming year after year! Expertly scored for beginning bands, this piece gives you the opportunity to teach the concept of "swing."

This celebrated Ukrainian carol ("Carol of the Bells") has been a favorite for generations! All of its excitement and vitality is expertly presented in Jeff Taylor's colorful and imaginative arrangement.

This processional march will be a perfect addition on many different programs. Solidly scored for younger players, it's characterized by a strong, tuneful melody and bold rhythms. Following a dramatic modulation, this stirring march leads to a glorious finale!

This delightful composition can be played either as a section feature, a duet or as a solo. Right down to the solo cadenza, CLARINETICS provides just the right amount of challenge and interest for your players.

Written as the finale to Jay's Western Suite. "JAMBOREE" works equally well as an individual selection. It is characterized by bold syncopated rhythms and strong melodic theme, reminiscent of some of the great Western movie scores.
A light rock ballad that's very playable yet with a surprising degree of sophistication and appeal. Can be effectively programmed as the second part of the Western Suite.
The rhythmic vitality and powerful melodies of this brilliant piece make it ideal as an individual number or combined with "Sunride" and/or "Jamboree" as part of Jay's Western Suite.
This sparkling composition features your entire flute section. Imaginatively scored in an appealing light rock style.

Great opener on any of your concert programs. Bright, bold harmonies and a strong, tuneful melody arranged so all sections of the band have interesting parts. Don't miss this colorfully and tuneful march!
Add the excitement of Spain to your next concert with this exciting composition. Plenty of audience appeal. Ole!
A delightful combination of the enchanting "Lavender Blue" and the stirring "Loch Lomond" in a lyrical arrangement that's interesting for all sections.
titre: Two Songs From the British Isles

description: This energetic disco-rock excursion will be a "sure-fire" success with both audience and band. Guaranteed!

Written to commemorate the release of the American hostages from their long imprisonment in Iran, this dynamic composition is characterized by powerful rhythms and bold harmonies. Mature sounding yet well within the technical limits of young players.
A haunting melody and lush harmonies combine in this exciting beguine that's extremely effective for young players.
Highly imaginative disco treatment of Yankee Doodle that's sure to be a hit with both your band and your audience!
Powerful melodic lines and an interesting modal flavor are features of this exciting march. An ideal choice for that important first concert.
Revive the "Spirit of '76" with this driving and dramatic march by Ralph Gingery. Excellent!

Two movements make up this outstanding composition. The first features lyrical flute and clarinet solo passages while the second movement contrasts with a faster tempo, strong themes and powerful ensemble sections. A great addition to the contest literature available at this level!
This bold march is loaded with power and drive! Makes a great addition to any of your programs, especially as a dramatic opener.

Here's something totally different! It's a musical adventure into thematic contrast and development which features the musical triumph of the "good guys" over some rather unsavory characters. Cleverly conceived and skillfully written for younger bands, it's sure to be a real favorite!

The exciting sounds of a Brazilian street festival complete with all the drums and whistles in a very easy arrangement for young bands. A great spotlight for the percussion section while not overly challenging the winds.

Here's a bold Spanish-flavored composition which features your trumpet soloist. Both an easy and more difficult version of the solo part are included. Powerfully scored for maximum sound, it's perfect for developing bands!

Your players will really "get-into" this rock number which reflects the break-dancing craze. It's easy to play and even includes some vocals from the band. Sure to score high with your performers and audience on any of your programs!

Revive the spirit of old New Orleans with this exciting arrangement which features a swing treatment of "Just A Closer Walk With Thee" and an easy, rousing arrangement of the perennial favorite, "When The Saints Go Marchin' In." You can't miss with this crowd-pleaser!

This outstanding arrangement opens dramatically with "When Johnny Comes Marching Home" then moves to a majestic treatment of "America, the Beautiful" before concluding with an easy yet very effective "Star Spangled Banner."
Interesting percussion colors highlight this lively and fun-to-play samba that fits the skills of first and second year players just right.
A brilliant contemporary overture by Jeff Taylor. Note how the forceful main theme contrasts perfectly with a lyrical middle section. All sections of the band have interesting parts.
This majestic and dynamic overture will be quickly learned and enjoyed by young performers. A very easy yet extremely effective selection.
This is guaranteed to be a winner with your players and audience! Authentic rock rhythms have been skillfully incorporated into a driving and energetic number that's perfect for young band.

This majestic arrangement of the traditional carol makes use of the theme and variations form. Each section of the band has an opportunity to play the melody in this imaginative and effective selection. Perfect for your holiday program!
Give your young group a chance to really "swing" with this fun concert-styled blues. A delightful change-of-pace selection that will be thoroughly enjoyed by band and audiences alike!
Jay Chattaway's stirring and beautiful work was written as a tribute to a young musician. It's a perfect piece for developing bands!
You can feature either an alto sax or trumpet soloist with this enchanting, pop-styled ballad. Your band will really enjoy performing it!
Here's a highly inventive treatment of this fine Christmas carol. It will certainly be an important addition to your holiday program.
This fine march-styled composition was written by one of the best composers of concert band literature. Use it to open or conclude any of your programs with real style!
Here's a superb and especially effective composition by Jeffrey Taylor. This brilliant concert work is powerful yet very playable.
Looking for a special piece to feature your trumpet section? This outstanding selection works incredibly well with young bands!
Here's an excellent overture which features contrasting tempos and solid scoring. You'll find it perfect for both festival and concert performances.
This is the concluding movement to Jay's Second Suite for Band. "Ceremony" also works great as an individual selection characterized by expressive lines and exciting powerful rhythms.
Powerful dynamic effects and dramatic sweeping melodic lines characterize this bold composition. Great as a individual selection or as the second movement of Jay's Second Suite for Band.
Imagine opening your next concert with this dramatic composition! Can be effectively programmed as the first movement of the Second Suite for Band.

This sparkling Christmas medley features well-known carols from England, France, and Germany. Although the principal songs featured are "Deck the Halls," "Lo How A Rose E'er Blooming," and "Bring a Torch Jeanette Isabella," the transitions utilize tuneful quotations of other carols associated with each country. Carefully and thoughtfully arranged for young bands!
This fresh contemporary ballad offers you the unique opportunity to feature your choice of soloists. Parts are included for solo trumpet, solo flute, solo clarinet and solo alto sax.
An outstanding rock-flavored original that will be an instant favorite with your band! They'll really come to life with this one!
This exceptionally fine band composition musically depicts a space voyage to a distant galaxy and its triumphant return to earth. Destined to become a favorite!
Jeff Taylor has written one of the best marches in the entire First Concert Series. It's easy yet very impressive in performance.
Here's a great way to introduce your band to music by Prokofiev. This whimsical march has been very skillfully adapted for band by Ralph Gingery.
The seasonal favorite "O, Tannenbaum" effectively presented in a series of jazzy variations. A sure-fire crowd pleaser!
A brilliant, stately march characterized by a strong, tuneful melody and bold rhythms. Don't pass this one up!
It takes just the right elements to make a great rock style work for young band. This one's got them all!
A perfect way to feature your entire sax section (altos and tenors.) This Latin-flavored original is a delight to play and to program.
